# ==========================================
# AUTOOPS 2.0 — CURSOR AI GOVERNANCE RULES
# ==========================================

You are working on AutoOps 2.0, a production-grade DevOps and observability platform.

The platform is intended to evolve into:
- a scalable SaaS platform
- a DevOps automation system
- a monitoring and observability platform
- an infrastructure management platform
- a CI/CD orchestration platform

All code, architecture, and infrastructure decisions must prioritize:
- scalability
- reliability
- maintainability
- observability
- security
- modularity
- production readiness

Follow ALL rules strictly.

# ==========================================
# CRITICAL SAFETY RULES
# ==========================================

NEVER:
- delete files without explicit approval
- overwrite working logic blindly
- remove infrastructure configs
- break backward compatibility intentionally
- rewrite architecture without approval
- generate fake/mock production implementations
- hardcode secrets or credentials
- expose tokens, passwords, or API keys
- disable authentication or authorization
- bypass security checks
- disable validation
- remove error handling
- use dangerous shell commands
- run destructive database operations automatically
- remove Docker/Kubernetes/Terraform files
- auto-upgrade dependencies blindly
- generate extremely large monolithic files
- mix frontend/backend responsibilities
- create circular dependencies
- use deprecated or abandoned libraries
- ignore TypeScript errors
- suppress linting without reason
- commit .env files
- leak sensitive information in logs
- create insecure API endpoints
- use eval or dangerous dynamic execution
- expose internal infrastructure publicly
- generate unnecessary complexity
- create tightly coupled architecture

Always prioritize safety and maintainability.

# ==========================================
# PROJECT ARCHITECTURE RULES
# ==========================================

Project structure must remain modular.

Allowed architecture:

/apps
/packages
/infra
/docs
/scripts

Applications:

/apps/dashboard
/apps/api
/apps/worker

Shared packages:

/packages/ui
/packages/types
/packages/config
/packages/logger
/packages/database
/packages/utils

Infrastructure:

/infra/docker
/infra/kubernetes
/infra/terraform
/infra/helm
/infra/nginx
/infra/prometheus
/infra/grafana

Rules:
- frontend code only inside dashboard
- backend APIs only inside api
- workers only inside worker
- shared logic only inside packages
- infrastructure only inside infra
- docs only inside docs

Never violate separation of concerns.

# ==========================================
# TECH STACK RULES
# ==========================================

Frontend:
- Next.js
- React
- TypeScript
- TailwindCSS
- shadcn/ui

Backend:
- Node.js
- Express
- TypeScript

Database:
- PostgreSQL
- Prisma ORM

Caching:
- Redis

Monitoring:
- Prometheus
- Grafana

Containers:
- Docker
- Docker Compose

Infrastructure:
- Kubernetes
- Terraform
- Helm

CI/CD:
- GitHub Actions
- Jenkins
- ArgoCD

Package manager:
- pnpm ONLY

Never use npm or yarn.

# ==========================================
# TYPESCRIPT RULES
# ==========================================

- Always use strict TypeScript.
- Never use any unless unavoidable.
- Prefer interfaces for object contracts.
- Define explicit return types.
- Avoid unsafe type assertions.
- Use zod for runtime validation.
- Use reusable DTOs and schemas.
- Never ignore TypeScript compiler warnings.
- Avoid deeply nested types.
- Use shared types from packages/types.

# ==========================================
# BACKEND RULES
# ==========================================

Backend architecture must follow layered architecture.

Required structure:

src/
  controllers/
  services/
  repositories/
  routes/
  middleware/
  validators/
  config/
  utils/
  types/
  jobs/

Rules:
- controllers remain thin
- business logic only in services
- database access only in repositories
- validate all request payloads
- sanitize all inputs
- use centralized error handling
- use async/await consistently
- use structured logging
- use RBAC authorization
- secure JWT implementation
- implement rate limiting
- implement request validation
- implement API versioning
- use dependency injection patterns where appropriate

Never place business logic inside controllers.

# ==========================================
# DATABASE RULES
# ==========================================

- Use PostgreSQL.
- Use Prisma ORM.
- Use UUIDs for identifiers.
- Never run destructive migrations automatically.
- Ask before schema changes.
- Use indexes appropriately.
- Use transactions where needed.
- Prefer soft deletes for important entities.
- Never expose raw SQL publicly.
- Optimize queries.
- Avoid N+1 queries.
- Use connection pooling.
- Validate DB changes carefully.

# ==========================================
# FRONTEND RULES
# ==========================================

- Use responsive design.
- Use reusable components.
- Keep components small and modular.
- Separate UI and business logic.
- Use server state management correctly.
- Use loading states.
- Use error boundaries.
- Use skeleton loaders where useful.
- Optimize rendering performance.
- Avoid prop drilling.
- Never hardcode API URLs.
- Use environment variables properly.

# ==========================================
# UI/UX RULES
# ==========================================

Design style:
- modern SaaS dashboard
- DevOps-focused UI
- clean layouts
- glassmorphism where appropriate
- accessible color contrast
- smooth animations
- professional spacing
- dark-mode friendly
- responsive on all devices

Dashboard modules:
- metrics
- logs
- deployments
- infrastructure health
- alerts
- Kubernetes status
- CI/CD pipelines
- system monitoring

# ==========================================
# DEVOPS RULES
# ==========================================

- Every service must be Dockerized.
- Use multi-stage Docker builds.
- Minimize image sizes.
- Use health checks.
- Use restart policies.
- Never run containers as root.
- Use environment variables correctly.
- Use .env.example files.
- Use volume persistence where appropriate.
- Add observability support.
- Add logging support.
- Add monitoring support.

# ==========================================
# KUBERNETES RULES
# ==========================================

- Use namespaces.
- Use ConfigMaps.
- Use Secrets properly.
- Use readiness probes.
- Use liveness probes.
- Define resource limits.
- Avoid hardcoded values.
- Use scalable deployments.
- Use Helm-compatible structure.
- Follow GitOps-friendly practices.

# ==========================================
# SECURITY RULES
# ==========================================

- Validate all inputs.
- Escape dangerous outputs.
- Prevent XSS.
- Prevent SQL injection.
- Prevent SSRF.
- Prevent CSRF.
- Use secure cookies.
- Use secure headers.
- Use HTTPS-ready configs.
- Implement RBAC.
- Implement audit logging.
- Never expose secrets.
- Never log credentials.
- Use secret rotation support.
- Use least-privilege principles.

# ==========================================
# PERFORMANCE RULES
# ==========================================

- Optimize database queries.
- Use pagination.
- Use caching intelligently.
- Optimize bundle sizes.
- Lazy load heavy components.
- Avoid memory leaks.
- Avoid blocking operations.
- Use efficient polling intervals.
- Optimize Docker layers.

# ==========================================
# LOGGING RULES
# ==========================================

- Use structured logging.
- Include timestamps.
- Include request IDs.
- Include service names.
- Never log secrets.
- Separate info/warn/error logs.
- Make logs observability-friendly.

# ==========================================
# TESTING RULES
# ==========================================

- Add unit tests for services.
- Add integration tests for APIs.
- Add validation tests.
- Add authentication tests.
- Add error handling tests.
- Never ship critical logic untested.
- Prefer deterministic tests.
- Avoid flaky tests.

# ==========================================
# DOCUMENTATION RULES
# ==========================================

Always update documentation for:
- architecture changes
- environment variables
- deployment flows
- infrastructure changes
- API changes
- monitoring setup
- Docker changes

Maintain:
- README
- architecture docs
- API docs
- deployment docs

# ==========================================
# GIT RULES
# ==========================================

Commit conventions:

feat:
fix:
refactor:
docs:
test:
chore:
infra:
security:

Rules:
- keep commits modular
- avoid huge commits
- avoid unrelated changes
- explain major infrastructure changes
- never commit secrets

# ==========================================
# AI BEHAVIOR RULES
# ==========================================

Before generating code:
- analyze existing architecture first
- reuse existing utilities
- avoid duplicate logic
- maintain consistency
- explain major risks

Before modifying files:
- explain affected areas
- explain dependencies
- explain migration impact

When uncertain:
- ask instead of guessing

Prefer:
- maintainability
- readability
- modularity
- scalability
over shortcuts.

# ==========================================
# AUTOOPS PLATFORM GOALS
# ==========================================

Primary goals:
- production-grade reliability
- scalability
- observability
- infrastructure automation
- security
- maintainability
- excellent developer experience
- enterprise-ready architecture

# ==========================================
# ABSOLUTE RESTRICTIONS
# ==========================================

ABSOLUTELY NEVER:
- destroy existing infrastructure
- remove auth/security
- expose secrets
- break production configs
- disable validation
- remove observability
- rewrite architecture blindly
- generate fake implementations
- introduce massive technical debt
- create unmaintainable code
- create insecure defaults
- generate unstable infrastructure
- perform destructive operations automatically
- create unnecessary abstractions
- overengineer simple modules
- underengineer critical systems